description: {"blocks":[{"key":"9fb9j","text":"This protocol describes the standard procedure of thawing human pluripotent stem cells (hPSCs) on inactivated mouse embryonic fibroblasts (MEFs).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"553jc","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5rc62","text":"General notes","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":13}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3vgh9","text":"1. Throughout this protocol, the term hPSC is used to collectively refer to both hiPSCs and hESCs. All described procedures have been tested and work equally well for hiPSCs and hESCs.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"650o5","text":"2. Until otherwise indicated, hPSCs are routinely grown in a humidified cell culture incubator under “low” oxygen conditions. We have successfully maintained hPSCs using either 3% O2 (3% O2, 5% CO2) or 5% O2 (5% O2, 5% CO2) conditions. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"67cud","text":"3. While freezing hPSCs as single cell solution (using Rock Inhibitor) results in better cell recovery, some laboratories prefer freezing of hPSCs as cell clusters. We have used both approaches and do not observe obvious differences.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"9k5md","text":"Prepare one 6-well MEFs plate for each vial of frozen hPSCs","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"f2e1o","text":"Place vial of frozen hPSCs in    water bath with constant agitation. {"blocks":[{"key":"2e2ju","text":"Add 1 ml hPSCs medium with or without Rock inhibitor (dependent on choice made above).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"5su7o","text":"Pipette the cells onto the 2 ml already on the MEFs.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"453k3","text":"Check the cells under the microscope to get an idea of the resulting cell density.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"egtal","text":"Spread the cells by moving the plate in left-right, then backward-forward motion.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"3mptp","text":"Place the plate in the low oxygen incubator","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"e42ah","text":"From day 3, change 2-3 ml pre-warmed hPSCs medium for each well daily.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"31fqo","text":"When large colonies emerge or hPSCs density reaches 50-70%, passage using collagenase. It usually takes 7-10 days for the thawed cells to grow to this point. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
